-- Spanish, Italian Borrowing Costs Rise at Today's Sales of Treasury Bills
-- Paul Dobson
-- 2010-04-27T11:06:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-27/spanish-bill-yields-advance-in-sales-of-3-month-6-month-debt-securities.html

          
          
             Spain and Italyâ€™s borrowing costs
rose as the nations sold 12 billion euros ($16 billion) of
bills.  
 Spain sold 1.7 billion euros of six-month securities to
yield 0.736 percent today, up from 0.482 percent at a sale on
March 23. It also issued 936 million euros of three-month bills
yielding 0.515 percent, compared with 0.324 percent at a March
23 sale.  
 Italy issued 9.5 billion euros of six-month notes at a
yield of 0.814 percent, from 0.568 percent at a March 26 sale.
The bid-to-cover ratio, a measure of demand for the securities,
fell to 1.02, from 1.56 in the previous sale.  
